"""
MKT Context Commentary — 2 Chronicles chapters 9–12
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2chronicles-9-12.py

Ch9: Queen of Sheba (Saba, SW Arabia) — diplomatic-commercial mission; Ophir gold; algum wood;
     ivory throne; Tarshish fleet; Solomon's international tribute system
Ch10: Rehoboam at Shechem — tribal assembly format; corvée grievance; "my little finger thicker
      than my father's loins" — body-politics taunt; divine causation of the schism
Ch11: Rehoboam's fortification network (Lachish, Adullam, Hebron etc.) — archaeological evidence;
      Jeroboam's cult innovations (golden calves, goat-idols, non-Levitical priests); Levitical
      migration south; Maacah granddaughter of Absalom as chief wife
Ch12: Shishak = Shoshenq I (Dynasty 22, 945-924 BCE) — Bubastite Portal at Karnak confirms invasion;
      year 5 of Rehoboam (ca. 925 BCE); bronze replacing gold as symbol of dynastic decline
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>The Queen of Sheba (<em>malkat Šᵉḇāʾ</em>) is identified with ancient Saba, a kingdom in southwestern Arabia (modern Yemen) whose capital Marib controlled the lucrative incense and spice trade routes from southern Arabia to the Mediterranean. The Sabaean kingdom is attested in Assyrian annals from the late 8th century BCE and in South Arabian inscriptions; the biblical account reflects the 10th-century BCE period when Sabaean trade dominance was establishing itself. The gifts she brings — spices, gold, precious stones — are precisely the products of the Arabian trade network. Her diplomatic visit served dual purposes: to assess Solomon's wisdom as a potential commercial ally and to establish favorable trade terms for the Sabaean incense route passing through Israelite-controlled territory. The <em>ḥîdôt</em> (difficult questions, riddles) she poses are the standard ANE test of royal wisdom: Mesopotamian and Egyptian texts record wisdom contests as a diplomatic genre.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s comprehensive answers demonstrate the universal wisdom that the Chronicler traces to YHWH&rsquo;s direct grant (cf. 1:11-12). The phrase <em>lōʾ-nᵉʿlam dāḇār miśŠelōmōh ʾăšer lōʾ-higîd lāh</em> (&lsquo;nothing was too difficult for him to explain&rsquo;) matches the wisdom-ideal of Egyptian and Mesopotamian royal ideology: the perfect king is the one who can answer all questions. The Sabaean queen as foreign royalty receiving complete answers elevates Solomon above his ANE contemporaries.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The queen&rsquo;s inspection tour covers both wisdom (verbal answers to riddles) and material culture: the palace Solomon had built is the administrative complex south of the temple described in 1 Kgs 7:1-12. Court architecture in this period served as a tangible demonstration of a ruler&rsquo;s resources and organizational capacity; palace design was diplomatic communication. The &lsquo;House of the Forest of Lebanon&rsquo; (cited in v16, 20) was the main palace hall, named for its cedar-column forest; it served as throne room, armory, and reception space.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The court ceremonial she observes — food arrangement, seating order, servants&rsquo; uniforms, cupbearers&rsquo; uniforms, and burnt offerings — reflects precisely the protocol visible in ANE palace administrative texts. Servant uniforms (<em>malbûšêhem</em>) were standardized markers of court rank; the existence of uniform codes signals bureaucratic sophistication. The inclusion of <em>ʿōlātô ʾăšer yaʿăleh bêt YHWH</em> (the burnt offerings at the LORD&rsquo;s house) among the palace splendors shows the Chronicler integrating cult observance into the display of Solomonic magnificence: the king&rsquo;s religious devotion is as impressive as his administrative wealth. She was &lsquo;breathless&rsquo; (<em>wᵉlōʾ-hāyāh bāh rûaḥ</em> = literally &lsquo;there was no spirit left in her&rsquo;).</p>",
    "5": "<p>The queen&rsquo;s affirmation — &lsquo;the report I heard in my own country about your words and your wisdom was true&rsquo; — is the international validation the Chronicler uses to establish Solomon as surpassing all national boundaries. This constitutes a foreign royal witness to Solomon&rsquo;s YHWH-given wisdom; the Chronicler records it as indirect testimony to YHWH&rsquo;s faithfulness to the Davidic covenant.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The queen&rsquo;s correction — &lsquo;not even half of your great wisdom was told to me&rsquo; — employs the rhetorical device of the &lsquo;half&rsquo; to signal that a famous reputation is an understatement. This hyperbolic tribute is a diplomatic formula also attested in Egyptian and Mesopotamian royal inscriptions where foreign dignitaries acknowledge a king&rsquo;s superiority beyond what could be communicated by reputation. The personal autopsy (&lsquo;I came and saw for myself&rsquo;) is cited as epistemologically superior to hearsay.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&lsquo;Blessed are your men&rsquo; (<em>ʾašrê ʾănāšêḵā</em>) — the beatitude-form (<em>ʾašrê</em> = blessed/fortunate) applied to Solomon&rsquo;s servants who hear his wisdom continually. This reflects ANE court ideology where proximity to the wise king is itself a form of blessing: Proverbs&rsquo; wisdom tradition assumes that access to wisdom is a form of divine gift. The servants&rsquo; good fortune is measured by their perpetual exposure to royal wisdom.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The queen&rsquo;s theological conclusion — &lsquo;because your God loved Israel and intended to sustain them forever, he made you their king to administer justice and righteousness&rsquo; — is remarkable as a Gentile queen&rsquo;s confession of YHWH&rsquo;s love for Israel as the motive for Solomon&rsquo;s appointment. The formula <em>mišpāṭ ûṣᵉdāqāh</em> (justice and righteousness) is the standard Israelite description of the ideal king&rsquo;s function (cf. Isa 9:6; Jer 22:3); the Sabaean queen uses the same theological vocabulary as the prophets. This verse is the theological summit of the Sheba narrative.</p>",
    "9": "<p>One hundred and twenty talents of gold = approximately 4.5 metric tons — an enormous diplomatic gift confirming the scale of Sabaean gold exports. The &lsquo;spices&rsquo; (<em>bᵉśāmîm</em>) are the primary commodity of the South Arabian trade route: frankincense and myrrh grown in the Dhofar region of Oman and exported north through the Hijaz. The remark &lsquo;there had never been spices like those&rsquo; reflects the specialized quality of Sabaean aromatics as the finest available. Archaeological excavations at Marib (ancient Saba) have confirmed sophisticated trade infrastructure from this period.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ophir — the source of the finest gold in the Hebrew Bible — is variously identified with East Africa (Somalia region), southwestern Arabia, or India (Gujarat coast). The most widely accepted location is the southern Arabian coast or East African coast, accessible by Red Sea navigation from Ezion-geber/Elath. Algum wood (<em>ʿaṣê ʾalgûmmîm</em>, also spelled almug in 1 Kgs 10:11-12) is identified by most scholars as sandalwood (<em>Pterocarpus santalinus</em>) native to Sri Lanka/India, suggesting transoceanic trade via Arabia. It is described as a luxury material used only for the finest appointments.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The algum wood is used for temple steps and musical instruments (<em>kinnōrôt wᵉnᵉḇālîm</em>, harps and lyres) — the finest imported timber reserved for the worship space and royal court culture. The remark &lsquo;nothing like them had ever been seen in Judah&rsquo; reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent use of superlative language to mark Solomon&rsquo;s reign as uniquely blessed. Temple musical instruments made from rare foreign wood symbolize the internationalization of Israelite worship culture under Solomon.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The reciprocal gift exchange — Solomon giving the queen &lsquo;everything she wanted and asked for, over and above what she had brought&rsquo; — follows the ANE diplomatic protocol of <em>tamartu</em> (reciprocal gift-giving between rulers). The king who gives more than he receives demonstrates superior resources. The queen&rsquo;s departure with her &lsquo;servants&rsquo; (<em>waʿăḇādêhā</em>) represents the conclusion of a formal diplomatic-commercial mission.</p>",
    "13": "<p>666 talents of annual gold revenue (also in 1 Kgs 10:14) = approximately 25 metric tons of gold per year. The specific figure 666 has been variously explained as a fiscal record from temple or palace archives, a round administrative number, or a Mesopotamian-style accounting total. Gold in this quantity came through multiple channels: tribute, trade, conquest spoils, and the Red Sea trade network. Comparable large-scale gold accumulation is attested in Egyptian and Mesopotamian royal treasury records from the same period (10th century BCE).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The additional income from merchants (<em>sōḥᵃrîm</em>), traders (<em>rōḵᵃlîm</em>), and Arabian kings reflects Israel&rsquo;s position as a nexus of the international trade routes connecting Egypt, Arabia, Mesopotamia, and the Mediterranean. &lsquo;Kings of Arabia&rsquo; (<em>malkê ʿăraḇ</em>) are the petty rulers of the Arabian trade-route cities who paid tribute for safe passage through Israelite-controlled territory. &lsquo;Regional governors&rsquo; (<em>paḥôt hāʾāreṣ</em>) are the provincial administrators of the empire&rsquo;s outer territories.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Two hundred large shields (<em>ṣinnōt</em>, the large body-shield) of hammered gold, each using 600 shekels (approximately 7 kg) of gold — purely ceremonial objects for display in the Hall of the Forest of Lebanon. These were not battle shields but processional or throne-room decorative pieces. The Assyrian reliefs from the 9th-7th centuries show similar decorative shields displayed in palace contexts. Their later theft by Shishak (12:9) and replacement with bronze (12:10) is one of the Chronicler&rsquo;s key symbols of dynastic decline.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Three hundred smaller shields (<em>māginnîm</em>) of hammered gold, each using 300 shekels (~3.5 kg) — the standard combat-size shield type. All were displayed in the House of the Forest of Lebanon, which served as both royal reception hall and armory. The total gold in the shields (2×200×600 + 3×300×300 shekel = 390,000 shekels = approximately 4.5 metric tons) represents a staggering commitment of metal to ceremonial display — a visible demonstration of royal wealth that matched ancient Near Eastern norms of conspicuous consumption by powerful kings.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s throne of ivory (<em>kissēʾ-šēn gādôl</em>) overlaid with pure gold is described in elaborate detail (vv17-19) that finds its closest ANE parallels in the throne descriptions of Ugaritic mythological texts and Assyrian palace reliefs. Ivory (<em>šēn</em>) was one of the most prestigious luxury materials of the ancient world, imported from Syria/Lebanon (elephant), Africa, or India; by the 10th century BCE, Phoenician craftsmen were renowned for ivory carving. Gold overlay on ivory furniture is attested archaeologically at Megiddo and at Samaria.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The throne design: six steps, gold footstool integrated into the throne structure (<em>keves zahāḇ lakkissēʾ mūḇāq</em>), armrests on each side, and lions beside the armrests. The lion (<em>ʾaryēh</em>) motif for royal thrones is ubiquitous in the ancient Near East: lion-flanked thrones appear in Phoenician, Egyptian, and Mesopotamian iconography as markers of royal power. Solomon&rsquo;s throne six steps high with twelve lions (v19) reflects a cosmic-ordered design: six steps × two lions per step = twelve, possibly corresponding to the twelve months or twelve tribes.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Twelve lions (<em>šᵉnê ʿāśār ʾărāyôt</em>) stood on the six steps — one lion at each side of each step. The statement &lsquo;nothing like it existed in any other kingdom&rsquo; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s superlative claim for Solomonic uniqueness. Lion-guarded thrones are attested in Canaanite, Phoenician, and Egyptian artistic contexts; what distinguishes Solomon&rsquo;s is the integration of the number twelve, the specifically Israelite symbolic number. The throne&rsquo;s elaborateness was doubtless also intended to impress foreign visitors like the Queen of Sheba.</p>",
    "20": "<p>All gold drinking vessels — <em>kol-kᵉlê mišqeh hamelekYitBaZāhāḇ</em> — and all the utensils of the House of the Forest of Lebanon in pure gold; &lsquo;silver was considered worthless in Solomon&rsquo;s day&rsquo; (<em>ʾên kesep nechšāḇ bîmê Šelōmōh lᵉmᵉʾûmāh</em>). This hyperbolic formulation (also in 1 Kgs 10:21) reflects the literary topos of the abundance that makes lesser wealth contemptible — a rhetorical formula also found in Egyptian and Mesopotamian royal inscriptions describing a king&rsquo;s wealth. Archaeologically, pure gold tableware is attested for royal courts of this period in the ancient Near East.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Tarshish fleet (<em>ʾoniyyôt Taršîš</em>) sailing every three years — Tarshish is most commonly identified with Tartessus in southwestern Spain (modern Huelva region), though some scholars locate it in Sardinia or Cilicia. The three-year voyage interval and the cargo list — gold, silver, ivory (<em>šēn</em>), apes (<em>qōpîm</em>), and peacocks (<em>tûkkiyyîm</em>) — suggests a long-distance maritime circuit. &lsquo;Peacocks&rsquo; may alternatively be rendered &lsquo;baboons&rsquo; (reading <em>tukkiyyim</em> as an Egyptian loanword for <em>ky</em>, baboon). The fleet&rsquo;s joint operation with Huram&rsquo;s crews reflects the Tyrian maritime expertise that made long-distance Phoenician trade possible.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&lsquo;Solomon surpassed all the kings of the earth in riches and wisdom&rsquo; — the summary statement positioning Solomon at the apex of the 10th-century BCE international order. This claim is the Chronicler&rsquo;s climactic evaluation after the wealth catalogue of ch9. The pairing of <em>ʿōšer</em> (wealth) and <em>ḥoḵmāh</em> (wisdom) reflects the original divine grant at Gibeon (1:11-12): Solomon received wisdom, and because of it, wealth beyond measure.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&lsquo;All the kings of the earth sought audiences with Solomon to hear the wisdom God had placed in his heart&rsquo; — the universal audience of foreign kings reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s idealization of Solomon&rsquo;s reign as a period of Israelite international prestige. <em>ḥoḵmāh ʾăšer-nātan ʾĕlōhîm bᵉlibbô</em> (the wisdom God placed in his heart) anchors the attraction in divine gift rather than human achievement. The pilgrimage of foreign kings to Israel is the eschatological pattern (Isa 60:1-7) temporarily previewed in Solomon&rsquo;s reign.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The annual tribute from all foreign kings includes: silver and gold objects (<em>kᵉlê kesep ûkᵉlê zāhāḇ</em>), clothing (<em>śalmōt</em>), myrrh (<em>nᵉkōʾt</em> — aromatic substances; cf. Gen 37:25), spices (<em>bᵉśāmîm</em>), horses (<em>sûsîm</em>), and mules (<em>pᵉrādîm</em>). The tribute list represents the luxury goods of the ancient Near Eastern economy: aromatics from Arabia, fine textiles from Syria/Phoenicia, horses from Cilicia and Egypt. The annual regularity (<em>šānāh bᵉšānāh</em>) indicates a formalized tributary system.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Four thousand stalls for horses and chariots (<em>ʾuryôt sûsîm ûmerkāḇôt ʾarbaʿat ʾălāpîm</em>) contrasts with 1 Kgs 4:26&rsquo;s 40,000 — a tenfold difference that is a well-known textual discrepancy. Most scholars regard the 4,000 of Chronicles as preserving the more accurate tradition (or reflecting different counting methods: stalls vs individual horses). Twelve thousand horsemen (<em>pārāšîm</em>) distributed between chariot cities and Jerusalem. Archaeological evidence from Megiddo has been cited for Solomonic stables, though the identification is debated; the stable-complex there is now more commonly dated to the Omride period.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&lsquo;From the Euphrates River to the land of the Philistines and down to the border of Egypt&rsquo; — the description of the ideal Solomonic kingdom matches the covenant promise of Gen 15:18 (from the river of Egypt to the great river, the Euphrates). This is the maximally extended form of the land promise, never fully achieved in practice but here attributed to Solomon&rsquo;s actual territorial control. The Chronicler&rsquo;s formulation parallels Ps 72:8 (&lsquo;from sea to sea, from the River to the ends of the earth&rsquo;), the royal ideal.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&lsquo;Silver as common as stone&rsquo; and &lsquo;cedar as plentiful as the sycamore trees of the foothills&rsquo; — the two hyperboles place Solomon&rsquo;s wealth in the context of local abundance. Sycamore (<em>šiqmāh</em>, Ficus sycomorus) was the common timber of the Shephelah lowlands, plentiful and cheap; cedar (<em>ʾerez</em>) was the prestige imported timber from Lebanon. Making cedar as common as sycamore is the ultimate statement of abundance. Similarly, silver as ordinary as Jerusalem&rsquo;s limestone — the comparison is to the stone of the city&rsquo;s own walls.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Horse imports from Egypt (<em>miMiṣrayim</em>) and &lsquo;from all other lands&rsquo; — the horse trade is attested in 1 Kgs 10:28-29 where Solomon is specifically described as a middleman in the horse trade between Egypt (Musri or Cilicia?) and the Hittites and Aramean kings. Egyptian chariot horses from the Nile Delta stud farms were prized throughout the ancient Near East; the Chronicler condenses this into a general summary. The Deuteronomic law (Deut 17:16) prohibits the king from multiplying horses or returning to Egypt for them — Solomon&rsquo;s horse trade is an implicit violation.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Three prophetic source documents are cited for Solomon&rsquo;s acts: (1) <em>diḇrê Nātān hannāḇîʾ</em> (the account of Nathan the prophet), (2) <em>nᵉḇûʾat ʾAḥiyyāh haŠŠîlōnî</em> (the prophecy of Ahijah the Shilonite, the prophet who announced the kingdom&rsquo;s division to Jeroboam, 1 Kgs 11:29-39), and (3) <em>ḥăzôt Yiddô hāḥōzeh ʿal-Yarobʿām</em> (the visions of Iddo the seer about Jeroboam). None of these documents has survived independently; the Chronicler uses them as source-citations to establish historical authority. The citation of prophetic sources alongside royal annals reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s view that prophetic interpretation is the proper framework for reading history.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s forty-year reign in Jerusalem matches the forty years in 1 Kgs 11:42. Forty years is a formulaically significant number in the Hebrew Bible (forty years in the wilderness, forty years for David&rsquo;s reign, forty years for Saul); whether the figure is exactly literal or schematic is debated. The reign length establishes Solomon as the parallel to David (also 40 years) — the two together constitute an eighty-year golden age of the united monarchy.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The standard succession formula: <em>wayyiškab Šelōmōh ʿim-ʾăḇōtāyw</em> and burial in the city of David. The Chronicler&rsquo;s account of Solomon ends here without recording Solomon&rsquo;s apostasy (1 Kgs 11) — the Chronicler systematically omits the narrative of Solomon&rsquo;s foreign wives and their gods, presenting a uniformly positive portrait. The succession formula <em>wayyimlōk Rᵉḥaḇʿām bᵉnô taḥtāyw</em> links immediately to ch10&rsquo;s crisis without the intervening explanation of divine judgment for apostasy that 1 Kgs 11 provides.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>Shechem (<em>Šᵉḵem</em>) was the traditional site of the tribal assembly of all Israel (cf. Gen 33:18-20; Josh 24:1; Judg 9). That Rehoboam must travel to Shechem (rather than being acclaimed in Jerusalem) signals immediately that the northern tribes are asserting constitutional rights: the king must come to them, not the reverse. Shechem was the covenant-renewal site of the conquest period and the seat of Abimelech&rsquo;s short-lived kingship (Judg 9). The northern tribes&rsquo; insistence on Shechem as the coronation location is a political statement about the limits of Davidic authority over them.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jeroboam&rsquo;s political exile in Egypt under Shishak (Shoshenq I, 945-924 BCE) — the same Pharaoh who will invade Judah in ch12 — reflects the complex Egyptian patronage of anti-Solomonic factions. First Kings 11:26-40 records that Ahijah the Shilonite prophesied to Jeroboam that he would rule ten tribes; Solomon therefore sought to kill him, forcing his flight to Egypt. Egyptian royal policy of harboring political exiles from neighboring states as potential leverage tools is well-attested in the New Kingdom and Third Intermediate Period diplomatic records.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The &lsquo;all Israel&rsquo; delegation to Rehoboam operates as the northern tribal assembly — a constitutional body with the right to negotiate terms of kingship. This reflects the conditional nature of Israelite monarchy (cf. 1 Sam 10:25; 2 Sam 5:3, where David makes a covenant with the elders before they acclaim him king). The presence of Jeroboam as the delegation&rsquo;s unofficial leader signals that the assembly has a pre-designated alternative candidate if Rehoboam refuses their terms.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&lsquo;Your father made our yoke heavy&rsquo; — the corvée grievance refers to the <em>mas</em> (forced labor) system Solomon imposed for building the temple, palace, and fortifications (cf. 1 Kgs 5:13-18; 9:15-22). While 1 Kgs 9:22 claims Israelites were not enslaved (only foreigners), 1 Kgs 5:13 records a levy of 30,000 Israelite workers. The contradiction reflects either two different labor policies or historical tension in the sources. The northern tribes&rsquo; complaint is rooted in concrete economic grievance: three decades of conscripted labor had drained their agricultural manpower.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The three-day deliberation period is standard ANE royal consultation practice, allowing time to convene advisors and formulate a response. Rehoboam&rsquo;s willingness to grant three days also signals that he is considering the request seriously — though his eventual rejection makes the delay functionally the preparation time for a catastrophically wrong decision. The three-day structure also creates narrative tension: the reader knows from v2 that Jeroboam is present, making the outcome foreshadowed.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The elders who served Solomon (<em>hazᵉqēnîm ʾăšer hāyû ʿōmᵉdîm lipnê Šelōmōh ʾāḇîw bᵉḥayyāyw</em>) represent accumulated political wisdom from a generation that had navigated the demands of both administration and tribal relationship. Their counsel reflects the classic ANE wisdom of the experienced courtier: conciliation is preferable to confrontation, and a king who binds his subjects through kindness secures more lasting loyalty than one who rules by force. Their advice is the standard of the <em>ḥākām</em> (wise counselor) genre.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&lsquo;If you will be generous to this people, please them, and speak kindly to them, they will be your loyal servants always&rsquo; — the elders&rsquo; counsel is the politics of consent: a king who conciliates creates durable loyalty. The phrase <em>dabbēr ʾălêhem ṭōḇîm</em> (&lsquo;speak kindly to them&rsquo;) uses the idiom of diplomatic speech in the ANE where &lsquo;good words&rsquo; = favorable terms. In the Amarna letters, subordinate kings routinely request &lsquo;good words&rsquo; (favorable responses) from the Pharaoh; the elders are deploying the same political vocabulary.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Rehoboam rejects the elder counsel and consults the young men (<em>hayᵉlādîm ʾăšer gadᵉlû ʾittô</em>) — his peers from the royal court who had grown up with him. The switch from the <em>zᵉqēnîm</em> (elders) to the <em>yᵉlādîm</em> (young men, literally &lsquo;children&rsquo;) in a single generation parallels the catastrophic advisory transition in the Rehoboam narrative and echoes the wisdom literature&rsquo;s consistent warning against rejecting the counsel of experience for the flattery of peers (Prov 12:15; 13:10). The Chronicler identifies the advisory switch as the narrative hinge on which the kingdom&rsquo;s fate turns.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The question Rehoboam poses to his contemporaries — &lsquo;what do you advise we tell these people?&rsquo; — is identical in form to the question posed to the elders (v6), but the framing differs: to the elders, he asked how to &lsquo;answer&rsquo; (<em>tāšîḇ</em>); to the young men, how to &lsquo;tell&rsquo; (<em>nᵉdabbēr</em>). The subtle shift from &lsquo;responding&rsquo; to &lsquo;speaking&rsquo; indicates that Rehoboam has already mentally shifted from negotiation to assertion.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&lsquo;My little finger is thicker than my father&rsquo;s waist&rsquo; (<em>qotanhî ʿābāh mimmotnê ʾāḇî</em>) — a body-comparison taunt using phallic-political imagery characteristic of ancient Near Eastern political rhetoric. The comparative diminishment of the predecessor through body-size comparison signals aggressive macho posturing. Similar body-politics rhetoric appears in Mesopotamian royal inscriptions where kings assert superiority over their fathers through militarist hyperbole. The young men&rsquo;s counsel has no diplomatic sophistication — it is an assertion of dominance through humiliation of the petitioners.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&lsquo;My father punished you with whips; I will use scorpions&rsquo; — the escalation from whips (<em>šōṭîm</em>) to scorpions (<em>ʿaqrabbîm</em>). &lsquo;Scorpions&rsquo; may refer to a specific type of multi-tipped whip or spiked implement (a type of flail with sharp tips), known from Roman scourging instruments; the term&rsquo;s precise referent is debated but clearly indicates a more severe punishment instrument. The threat is rhetorically self-defeating: threatening to be worse than an already-resented predecessor guarantees resistance. The young men&rsquo;s counsel is the paradigm of politically catastrophic advice.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The third-day return of Jeroboam and all the people fulfills the king&rsquo;s instruction and simultaneously constitutes the constitutional threshold: the assembly has properly awaited the king&rsquo;s response. The inclusion of &lsquo;as the king had instructed&rsquo; (<em>kaʾăšer dibber hammelek</em>) confirms that the assembly honored the process; it is Rehoboam who will violate the implicit covenant, not the northerners.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Rehoboam&rsquo;s &lsquo;harsh answer&rsquo; (<em>qāšāh ʾāḇîw ʾet-ʿûlam</em> — he made the yoke heavy) — the Chronicler&rsquo;s summary judgment on the response before quoting it. The rejection of elder counsel (<em>zāḇ ʾet-ʿăṣat hazᵉqēnîm</em>) is repeated as the explicit explanation for the catastrophe: it is not divine necessity but political folly that causes the schism (though v15 then adds the theological dimension).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The young men&rsquo;s formula repeated verbatim in Rehoboam&rsquo;s actual speech — father&rsquo;s heavy yoke → I will make it heavier; whips → scorpions. The verbatim repetition emphasizes that Rehoboam adopted the young men&rsquo;s exact phrasing rather than tempering it. In diplomatic contexts, the choice to quote the most aggressive advisors verbatim rather than softening into one&rsquo;s own words signals either political naivety or a deliberate choice to dominate rather than negotiate.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&lsquo;This turn of events was from God, so that the LORD could fulfill the word he had spoken through Ahijah the Shilonite to Jeroboam son of Nebat&rsquo; — the Chronicler&rsquo;s theological explanation places divine sovereignty behind the human folly. Ahijah&rsquo;s prophecy (1 Kgs 11:29-39) predicted the ten-tribe division as judgment for Solomon&rsquo;s idolatry; the Chronicler&rsquo;s omission of Solomon&rsquo;s sins means this verse is the only place where that prophetic word is referenced. The phrase <em>kibbāh nᵉqûḇāh mᵉʾet hāʾĕlōhîm</em> (&lsquo;this turn of events was from God&rsquo;) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s standard formula for divine sovereignty working through human decisions.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&lsquo;What share do we have in David? We have no inheritance in the son of Jesse&rsquo; — the schism slogan appears verbatim from 2 Sam 20:1, where Sheba ben Bichri raised it as a rebel against David. The recycling of the anti-Davidic rally cry signals that the tension between David&rsquo;s house and the northern tribes was a persistent structural feature of the united monarchy, not a sudden innovation. The phrase <em>rᵉʾēh bêtᵉḵā Dāwîd</em> (&lsquo;see to your own house, David!&rsquo;) is a formal declaration of political separation. &lsquo;Every Israelite, to your tents!&rsquo; is the demobilization formula from the period of the amphictyony, now redeployed as a declaration of secession.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The continuing rule over the Israelites in Judah&rsquo;s towns — Rehoboam retains the southern tribes (Judah and Benjamin, with Levites and some faithful northerners per ch11). The territorial division is not complete at this point; vv17-19 establish the political reality while the prophetic restraint (ch11:1-4) prevents military resolution. The Chronicler uses &lsquo;the Israelites living in the towns of Judah&rsquo; to maintain the inclusive Israelite identity even for the southern kingdom — they are not simply &lsquo;Judah&rsquo; but Israelites in Judah.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Hadoram (<em>Hădōrām</em>, also called Adoram/Adoniram in 1 Kgs 12:18 and 4:6) was the chief administrator of the corvée labor system — the same system that generated the northern tribes&rsquo; grievance. Sending the corvée administrator to negotiate with the rebelling labor force was a catastrophically tone-deaf political move. The stoning (<em>wayyirgemû-ḇô Yiśrāʾēl ʾeḇen wayyāmot</em>) was the crowd&rsquo;s response to seeing the symbol of their oppression. Rehoboam&rsquo;s flight in his chariot (<em>wayyitʾamēṣ hammelek ʿălôt hammerkaḇāh</em>) signals the complete collapse of northern authority.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&lsquo;Israel has been in rebellion against the house of David to this day&rsquo; — the historian&rsquo;s perspective formula (<em>ʿad hayyôm hazzeh</em>, to this day) anchors the narrative in the time of writing and confirms the permanent nature of the division. For the Chronicler writing after the Babylonian exile, this &lsquo;to this day&rsquo; encompasses the entire divided monarchy period through the Assyrian deportation of the north (722 BCE). The Chronicler&rsquo;s pan-Israelite vision throughout his work makes this standing schism a persistent theological wound.</p>"
  },
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>Rehoboam&rsquo;s mobilization of Judah and Benjamin (180,000 warriors) for civil war represents the maximum military capacity of the two southern tribes. The number may be schematic (the same as Saul&rsquo;s force in 1 Sam 11:8), but the specific figure of 180,000 <em>bᵉḥar baḥûrê milḥāmāh</em> (select warriors) signals a serious mobilization rather than a token force. The campaign&rsquo;s stated goal — &lsquo;to battle Israel and reclaim the kingdom&rsquo; — represents Rehoboam&rsquo;s attempt to reverse the schism by force.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Shemaiah the man of God (<em>ʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) appears only in the Chronicler&rsquo;s narratives of Rehoboam (here and ch12); he is not mentioned in 1 Kgs 12 (where the divine word comes anonymously in 1 Kgs 12:22-24). The Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent use of named prophets as the vehicles for divine intervention is a structural feature of his historiography: every major event has a prophetic voice interpreting it. The formula <em>wayhî dᵉḇar-YHWH ʾel-Šᵉmaʿyāhû</em> (the word of YHWH came to Shemaiah) is the standard prophetic oracle-reception formula.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The oracle is addressed to &lsquo;Rehoboam son of Solomon, king of Judah, and to all Israel in Judah and Benjamin&rsquo; — the Chronicler&rsquo;s characteristic inclusivity: even the southern kingdom is &lsquo;all Israel&rsquo; in Judah and Benjamin. This framing is theologically significant: the Chronicler never concedes that the northern kingdom is the &lsquo;real&rsquo; Israel; for him, the remnant community centered in Jerusalem maintains the true Israelite identity.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&lsquo;You are not to march out or fight against your fellow Israelites&rsquo; — <em>ʾaḥêḵem</em> (your brothers/fellow Israelites): the Chronicler maintains the kinship language for the northern tribes throughout, refusing the sharp nationalist separation that the schism might suggest. The reason: <em>kî mēʾittî nihyᵉtāh haddāḇār hazzeh</em> (&lsquo;this has come about through me&rsquo;) — divine causation of the division makes military reversal an act of resistance against YHWH. The obedience to the oracle — <em>wayyišmᵉʿû lᵉdiḇrê YHWH</em> — is one of Rehoboam&rsquo;s few acts of positive faithfulness.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The fortification program that follows the aborted civil war is the Chronicler&rsquo;s evidence of Rehoboam&rsquo;s constructive energy after accepting the schism. The defensive network is strategically oriented toward the south and southwest — the direction from which Egyptian invasion would come (and did come, ch12). Archaeological surveys of the Iron Age IIA period (10th century BCE) have identified fortified sites in the Shephelah and Negev consistent with a Rehoboam-era defensive network, though the exact dating of individual sites is debated.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Bethlehem, Etam, and Tekoa form a chain of fortified towns south of Jerusalem running toward Hebron and the Judean desert. Bethlehem (David&rsquo;s home city) has strategic importance as the first fortification south of Jerusalem on the ridge route. Etam is identified with Khirbet el-Khokh southwest of Bethlehem. Tekoa (hometown of Amos, Amos 1:1) is on the eastern rim of the Judean highlands overlooking the Dead Sea wilderness.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Beth-zur, Soco, and Adullam are located in the Shephelah (western foothills) — the key entry corridor from the coastal plain into the Judean highlands. Beth-zur (Khirbet et-Tubeiqah) guarding the road from Hebron to Jerusalem was fortified already in the Bronze Age; its strategic position made it one of the most contested sites in the region. Soco (Khirbet ʿAbbad) and Adullam (Tell esh-Sheikh Madhkur, the cave of David&rsquo;s outlaw years, 1 Sam 22:1) anchor the central Shephelah defense.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Gath (Tell es-Safi, identified with Philistine Gath), Mareshah (Tell Sandahanna), and Ziph (Tell Zif) represent the southwestern outer defense line. Gath&rsquo;s inclusion is historically interesting: if this is Philistine Gath, its fortification by Rehoboam implies that Israelite control had extended into formerly Philistine territory during Solomon&rsquo;s reign. Alternatively, this may be a different Gath. Mareshah becomes an important Hellenistic city later (cf. 2 Chr 14:9-10).</p>",
    "9": "<p>Adoraim, Lachish, and Azekah form a southern and southwestern line. Lachish (Tell ed-Duweir) is the most archaeologically significant site in Judah after Jerusalem: its Level IV fortification is associated with the Iron IIA period and may represent Rehoboam-era strengthening, though the most famous fortification (Level III) dates to the Hezekiah period. Azekah (Tell Zakariyeh) commands the Elah valley — the approach to Jerusalem from Gath — and appears in the Lachish Ostraca (586 BCE).</p>",
    "10": "<p>Zorah, Aijalon, and Hebron complete the fortification list. Zorah (the hometown of Samson, Judg 13:2) anchors the northern Shephelah. Aijalon guarded the important pass from the coastal plain to Jerusalem (the valley of Aijalon, Josh 10:12). Hebron, the southernmost listed city and a major patriarchal site (Abraham, David&rsquo;s first capital), is the southern anchor of the defensive system. The total of fifteen cities (vv6-10) reflects a strategic defensive perimeter protecting the Judean highlands from western and southern attack.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The military organization of the fortified cities includes appointed commanders (<em>nᵉśîʾîm</em>), food stores (<em>māʾăḵāl</em>), olive oil (<em>šemen</em>), and wine (<em>yayim</em>) — the standard logistical provisioning for garrison sites capable of withstanding siege. This logistical preparation reflects the ANE practice of stockpiling three-to-five years of food in fortified cities (cf. the Assyrian siege of Lachish in 701 BCE, which required significant Assyrian logistics for an extended assault). The stores of oil and wine were also valuable trade commodities.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Shields and spears (<em>ṣinnôt ûrᵉmāḥîm</em>) stocked in each fortified city — the standard defensive weapon complement. The shields (<em>ṣinnôt</em>, large body shields) and spears complement the city walls to equip garrison troops for defense without external resupply. The summary: &lsquo;Judah and Benjamin remained his&rsquo; — the political territorial reality consolidated through the fortification program. Benjamin&rsquo;s continued loyalty to the Davidic house is significant given Benjamin&rsquo;s geographical position straddling the boundary with the Northern Kingdom.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The voluntary alignment of priests and Levites with Rehoboam from throughout Israel is the Chronicler&rsquo;s unique contribution to the schism narrative (not in 1 Kings). Their migration south represents a massive religious-demographic shift: the qualified cult personnel abandon their northern posts and relocate to where legitimate Davidic kingship and YHWH-worship are centered. This creates the theological argument that the Jerusalem community, not the northern cult sites, represents the continuation of authentic Israelite worship.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Jeroboam&rsquo;s expulsion of the Levites from their priestly duties (<em>gēraš min-mᵉšarᵉtê kohen liYHWH</em>) — a religious restructuring of the northern cult to establish independence from Jerusalem. The Levitical pasture lands (<em>migrᵉšêhem waʾaḥuzātām</em>) in the north were abandoned; the Levites came as refugees to Judah. This migration became the demographic foundation for the Chronicler&rsquo;s claim that the southern kingdom was more authentically Israelite: it received the qualified religious personnel while the north operated with non-qualified substitute priests.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Jeroboam&rsquo;s cult installations: priests for <em>habbāmôt</em> (high places), for <em>haśśᵉʿîrîm</em> (goat-idols/satyrs; the same term used for the goat-demons in Lev 17:7), and for <em>hāʿᵉgālîm</em> (the golden calves). The golden calves at Bethel and Dan (1 Kgs 12:28-29) drew on the iconographic tradition of the bull/calf as a pedestal for the divine presence — the same tradition that Aaron&rsquo;s golden calf (Exod 32) exploited. Whether the calves were intended as images of YHWH or of other gods is debated; Jeroboam&rsquo;s proclamation (&lsquo;here are your gods who brought you up from Egypt&rsquo;) adapts the Exodus confessional formula and implies YHWH-identification.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The faithful northerners who &lsquo;had determined to seek the LORD God of Israel&rsquo; (<em>nōtᵉnîm ʾet-liḇbām liḇqōš ʾet-YHWH ʾĕlōhê Yiśrāʾēl</em>) migrate to Jerusalem &lsquo;to offer sacrifices to the LORD.&rsquo; The Chronicler&rsquo;s pan-Israelite concern is manifest: faithful individuals from every northern tribe maintain access to authentic worship by traveling to Jerusalem. The formula <em>nātan lēḇ</em> (set one&rsquo;s heart) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s idiom for genuine religious commitment (cf. 12:14 where Rehoboam&rsquo;s failure is precisely not doing this).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Three years of faithfulness — they &lsquo;followed the path of David and Solomon&rsquo; for three years. The three-year period (also the period before Rehoboam&rsquo;s apostasy in 12:1) suggests a pattern: an initial period of faithfulness followed by gradual decline. The Chronicler&rsquo;s theology of immediacy (retribution/reward proportional to current behavior) is illustrated here: the three faithful years correspond to a period of blessing, while the subsequent apostasy brings immediate punishment.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Rehoboam&rsquo;s wives: Mahalath daughter of Jerimoth son of David — making her a granddaughter of David by a son not listed in the main Davidic genealogies (Jerimoth is otherwise unknown). Abihail daughter of Eliab son of Jesse — making her a great-granddaughter of Jesse through David&rsquo;s older brother Eliab (1 Sam 16:6-7; 17:13). Both marriages thus connect Rehoboam to the Davidic family tree through collateral lines, consolidating dynastic identity through endogamous marriage.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The three sons of Mahalath: Jeush, Shemariah, and Zaham — none of whom became significant; they are listed only here. The Chronicler records genealogical details absent from Kings to document the Judean royal family structure and succession politics. Genealogical completeness is a consistent Chronicler interest, as demonstrated by the extensive genealogical material of 1 Chronicles 1-9.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Maacah daughter of Absalom — the identification creates a genealogical puzzle. Absalom had only one daughter, Tamar (2 Sam 14:27), not Maacah. Either this is a different Absalom, or Maacah is Tamar renamed, or she is a granddaughter through Tamar. Some identify her as a granddaughter of Absalom (daughter of his son Tamar&rsquo;s brother). The four sons she bears (Abijah, Attai, Ziza, Shelomith) include the eventual heir Abijah, making Maacah&rsquo;s identification a matter of dynastic importance.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Rehoboam had 18 wives (<em>nāšîm</em>) and 60 concubines (<em>pîlagšîm</em>) — 28 sons and 60 daughters. The harem size is far less than Solomon&rsquo;s (1 Kgs 11:3: 700 wives, 300 concubines) but follows the same ANE royal practice of large harems as demonstrations of wealth and mechanisms for diplomatic alliance through marriage. The Chronicler notes that Maacah was his most-loved wife (<em>ʾāhaḇ ʾet-Maʿăḵāh bat-Aḇšālôm min-kol-nāšāyw ûmipîlagšāyw</em>), which explains the succession decision in v22.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The appointment of Abijah as <em>lᵉrōʾš lᵉʾeḥāyw</em> (chief among his brothers) and designated successor reflects the ANE practice of the king formally designating his heir while still living. The designation of a non-firstborn son as crown prince (if Abijah was not the eldest) requires override of primogeniture — consistent with the Chronicler&rsquo;s theme that YHWH&rsquo;s election supersedes birth-order (cf. the recurring pattern of younger-son selection from Abel through Joseph through David).</p>",
    "23": "<p>Rehoboam&rsquo;s &lsquo;shrewd&rsquo; (<em>wayyāśem bᵉḇînāh</em>) distribution of his sons throughout the districts — placing them in fortified cities with generous provisions (<em>māʾăḵāl lārōḇ</em>) and arranging many marriages (<em>wayyišʾal hāmôn nāšîm</em>) — is an astute piece of dynastic management. By distributing non-heir sons to fortified cities with resources and marriage alliances, Rehoboam both prevented court intrigue (removed rival claimants from the capital) and strengthened regional loyalty by embedding royal family members throughout Judah. This was standard ANE practice for managing large royal families.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>&lsquo;Once Rehoboam&rsquo;s rule was secure and he had grown strong&rsquo; (<em>ûkᵉhikkîn mamleket Rᵉḥaḇʿām wᵉḵeḥezqātô ʾāzaḇ ʾet-tôrat YHWH</em>) — the Chronicler&rsquo;s structural pattern of security leading to apostasy is first established here and recurs throughout the history (cf. 26:16 for Uzziah). The verb <em>ʿāzaḇ</em> (abandoned) for leaving the Torah creates the direct cause-and-effect the Chronicler uses systematically: faithfulness brings strength; strength leads to abandonment; abandonment brings judgment; judgment produces humbling; humbling brings partial restoration.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Shishak (<em>Šîšaq</em>) = Shoshenq I, founder of Egypt&rsquo;s 22nd Dynasty (945-924 BCE), the first major pharaoh of the Third Intermediate Period whose military campaigns are archaeologically confirmed. The Bubastite Portal at Karnak temple lists over 150 city names from Shoshenq&rsquo;s Palestinian campaign, including sites in Judah, the Negev, and the northern kingdom. The date — &lsquo;the fifth year of King Rehoboam&rsquo; — corresponds to approximately 925 BCE by conventional chronology. The force described: 1,200 chariots and 60,000 cavalry, plus an innumerable infantry, represents an overwhelming military superiority over Judah&rsquo;s defensive capacity.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The coalition army: Libyans (<em>Lûḇîm</em>), Sukkiim (<em>Sukkiyyîm</em>), and Cushites (<em>Kûšîm</em>). The Libyans were the ethnic base of the 22nd Dynasty itself — Shoshenq was of Libyan origin, as were many of his officers. The Sukkiim are unknown from other ancient sources; they may be a Libyan tribal group or possibly Nubian mercenaries. The Cushites (from the Nubian/Sudanese region) were a significant component of Egyptian mercenary forces throughout the Late Bronze and Iron Ages. This multinational composition reflects the structure of Egyptian Late Period military forces, which relied heavily on Libyan and Nubian contingents.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The capture of the fortified cities Rehoboam had just built (ch11) — the irony is pointed: the cities built in anticipation of external threat fell immediately to the first external attack. This rapid collapse may indicate that the fortification program was incomplete, that the garrisons were undermanned, or that the Chronicler is making a theological point: defenses without faithfulness to YHWH are ineffective. Several of the cities named in ch11 appear in Shoshenq&rsquo;s campaign list on the Bubastite Portal at Karnak.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Shemaiah&rsquo;s second oracle (cf. 11:2-4) interprets the Shishak invasion as direct consequence of Judah&rsquo;s abandonment of YHWH. The <em>lex talionis</em> formulation — &lsquo;you abandoned me, so I have now abandoned you to Shishak&rsquo; (<em>ʾatem ʿăzaḇtem ʾōtî wᵉgam-ʾănî ʿāzaḇtî ʾetḵem bᵉyad Šîšaq</em>) — echoes the ʿāzaḇ (abandon) vocabulary of v1 with precise chiastic structure. The prophet arrives at Jerusalem precisely when the Judean leaders are assembled there because of Shishak — divine timing of prophetic word to political crisis.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&lsquo;The Judean leaders and the king humbled themselves&rsquo; (<em>wayikkānᵉʿû śārê Yiśrāʾēl wᵉhammelek</em>) — <em>kānaʿ</em> (H3665): to humble oneself, submit, bow down. This humbling is the Chronicler&rsquo;s pivotal theological response — the same verb used for the paradigmatic humble response in 7:14 (&lsquo;if my people humble themselves...&rsquo;). The declaration <em>ṣaddîq YHWH</em> (&lsquo;the LORD is just&rsquo;) is a judicial acknowledgment that YHWH&rsquo;s punishment is deserved — the most theologically significant confession possible and the precondition for divine relenting.</p>",
    "7": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s response to their humbling: <em>niktānᵉʿû lōʾ ʾašḥîtēm</em> (&lsquo;they have humbled themselves, so I will not destroy them&rsquo;) — the mechanics of divine relenting in Chronicles. The phrase <em>nātattî lāhem kitmêtāh mᵉʿaṭ</em> (&lsquo;I will grant them limited deliverance&rsquo;) — literally &lsquo;a little escape&rsquo; (<em>mᵉʿaṭ</em> = little/limited) rather than complete salvation. The Chronicler&rsquo;s theology of partial deliverance: repentance brings relief, but does not erase the consequences of sin entirely. The Shishak invasion proceeds; only the total destruction is averted.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&lsquo;They will become his subjects... so they will learn the difference between serving me and serving the kings of foreign nations&rsquo; — <em>lᵉmaʿan yidᵉʿû ʿăḇōdātî ûʿăḇōdat mamlᵉḵôt hāʾărāṣôt</em>. The pedagogical purpose of subjugation is the Chronicler&rsquo;s unique theological insight: the experience of foreign servitude teaches by contrast what it means to serve YHWH. The Egyptian vassal relationship — with its tribute demands, loss of autonomy, and foreign oversight — is YHWH&rsquo;s teaching instrument. This verse is the theological center of the Shishak narrative.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Shishak carries off the temple treasures and the gold shields Solomon had made — the complete reversal of the wealth accumulation narratives of chs4-5 and 9. The specific mention of <em>ûmāginnê hazzāhāḇ ʾăšer ʿāśāh Šelōmōh</em> (the gold shields Solomon made) connects the golden shields of 9:15-16 to their confiscation here, creating a narrative arc from abundance to loss. Shoshenq&rsquo;s Karnak inscription records the plunder taken from Palestinian campaigns, consistent with the Chronicler&rsquo;s account.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The bronze shields as replacement (<em>taḥtêhem ʿāśāh māginnê nᵉḥōšet</em>) — the gold-to-bronze substitution is a deliberate symbol of dynastic decline. In the ANE, the sequence gold → silver → bronze → iron connoted descending value (cf. the Hesiodic ages of metals; Dan 2:32-33). Bronze replacing gold for the ceremonial royal shields reduces their visual impact from the gleaming gold that impressed the Queen of Sheba to a functional but humble substitute. The shields still perform their ritual function but no longer display imperial wealth.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The guard ritual — the royal guards carry the bronze shields when the king enters the LORD&rsquo;s house and then return them to the guardroom (<em>tāʾ harāṣîm</em>) — preserves the ceremonial function of the shields despite their material diminishment. The institutionalization of the carrying procedure suggests that the shields became part of a fixed royal ceremonial protocol. The <em>tāʾ</em> (guardroom) is a specific architectural feature of the palace guard complex adjacent to the temple entrance.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&lsquo;Because he humbled himself, the LORD&rsquo;s anger turned from him and did not destroy him completely&rsquo; (<em>ûbᵉhikkanᵉʿô šāḇ mimmennû ʾap-YHWH wᵉlōʾ lᵉhašḥît lᵉḵālāh</em>) — the precise mechanics of partial deliverance: <em>hašḥît lᵉḵālāh</em> (utter destruction) is averted; partial subjugation is the mitigated punishment. <em>ûḇᵉYᵉhûdāh hāyû dᵉḇārîm ṭōḇîm</em> (&lsquo;indeed, things went well in Judah&rsquo;) — the <em>dᵉḇārîm ṭōḇîm</em> (good things/conditions) despite the subjugation is the positive residue of partial repentance. The Chronicler&rsquo;s nuanced theology: repentance brings real improvement even when it doesn&rsquo;t produce full restoration.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The accession formula: 41 years old at accession, 17-year reign, Jerusalem. The mother&rsquo;s name — Naamah the Ammonite (<em>Naʿămāh hāʿammônît</em>) — is repeated from 1 Kgs 14:21, 31. Naamah was a foreign wife of Solomon, making Rehoboam the son of one of Solomon&rsquo;s diplomatic marriages. The explicit note of Ammonite heritage is likely the Chronicler&rsquo;s subtle indication that mixed ethnic heritage contributed to Rehoboam&rsquo;s religious instability. Jerusalem is identified as &lsquo;the city the LORD chose from all Israel&rsquo;s tribes as the place for his name&rsquo; — the election formula underlying the entire Davidic-Jerusalem theology.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&lsquo;He did evil because he did not commit himself to seeking the LORD&rsquo; (<em>wayyaʿaś hāraʿ kî lōʾ-hēḵîn liḇḇô liḏrōš ʾet-YHWH</em>) — the Chronicler&rsquo;s final verdict on Rehoboam. The idiom <em>hēḵîn lēḇ</em> (prepare/commit the heart) is the same as David&rsquo;s preparation of materials for the temple (1 Chr 29:18-19). The failure is not one act of apostasy but a disposition: Rehoboam never formed the fundamental orientation toward seeking YHWH. <em>dāraš ʾet-YHWH</em> (seeking the LORD) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s master criterion for evaluating kings; its absence explains all the apostasy and its consequences.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The source citations for Rehoboam&rsquo;s acts: <em>diḇrê Šᵉmaʿyāhû hannāḇîʾ wᵉʿIddô hāḥōzeh</em> (the writings of Shemaiah the prophet and Iddo the seer) in their genealogical records (<em>bᵉhityaḥēś</em>). Iddo the seer appears as a source in 9:29 and 13:22 as well; the Chronicler treats prophetic writings as primary historical sources. The note about &lsquo;constant wars between Rehoboam and Jeroboam throughout his reign&rsquo; (<em>ûmilḥᵃmôt Rᵉḥaḇʿām wîrāḇʿām kol-hayyāmîm</em>) compresses years of border conflict into a single clause — the Chronicler is uninterested in military history per se but records the fact of standing conflict.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The burial formula — <em>wayyiškab Rᵉḥaḇʿām ʿim-ʾăḇōtāyw wayyiqqāḇēr bᵉʿîr Dāwîd</em> — places Rehoboam in the royal tomb sequence despite his failures. Burial in the city of David remains available to him because he humbled himself before YHWH (v12): the partial repentance secures the minimum dynastic honor. His son Abijah succeeds him — the child Rehoboam had already designated in 11:22, confirming that the succession plan executed without disruption despite the political and military upheavals of the reign.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', '2chronicles')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '2chronicles', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'2chronicles mkt-context ch9-12: wrote {count} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
